Traders said the currency’s next move would likely be higher towards R13.60 as sentiment remains bearish due to the simmering trade row between China and the United States. JOHANNESBURG - The rand edged lower on Wednesday in a subdued morning session. At 0630 GMT the rand was 0.06% weaker at R13.5525 per dollar. Traders said the currency’s next move would likely be higher towards R13.60 as sentiment remains bearish due to the simmering trade row between China and the United States. Safe-haven assets remain in favour, traders said, with short rand plays targeting R13.20 and stops above R13.80. "We need a break of either R13.6500 or R13.4500 to shake things up again but at this stage hard to see what is going to push it, analysts at Nedbank said in a note. Bonds were also barely changed, with the yield on the benchmark paper due in 2026 up 0.5 basis points to 8.885%. Stocks were due to open lower when trade commences at 0700 GMT, with the JSE Top-40 futures index down almost 0.4%.